At first I tried to force an amount of time pressure by stating that I had a doctor's appointment to attend. This was to try and force them to rush through their questions and to not dwell on any of my answers for too long at a time. I brought this up again later while the interview was looking through their notes to try and create urgency and not allow them additional time to think.

I didn't want to lie completely to the interviewer as if they had concrete evidence that I had taken a particular action or been in a certain area they might have been able to catch me in a lie. I tried to give a little bit of truth in terms of certain areas that I had been, the basement, the balcony, the 5th floor, and tried to create a reasonable excuse for why I had been there. I also tried to remain vague and hazy in my memory about specific details so that if a line of questioning was followed up on I would be able to feign confusion or claim I had made a mistake.

I denied knowledge of technology and politics when asked, I felt this could be risky as it might raise suspicion slightly but alternatively, admitting to this could immediately put the interview into a guilty mindframe.

I promised to make myself available over the next few days and offered details that would take time to check, knowing that I would not be returning and that although my story may not hold up on further inspection, I may be believed to be innocent in the moment and so I would not be held immediately for further interrogation.

strategy_free:
My initial plan was to be a little bit emotional and a little disoriented. So at the outset I explained to the interviewer that I was feeling emotional and a little troubled, and that I had had some alcohol to drink (which is always great for reasonable doubt)

Initially I did not know how much detail the interviewer had, but the moment I realised that he did have access to CCTV footage, I knew that it was imperative for me to preempt some of his questions. This also meant that it was important for me to give an accurate account of the locations I went to in the building since the interviewer had knowledge of that. I also knew that I was wearing gloves the entire time, so my hopes were that the video footage would have been a little inconclusive, and I knew that my finger prints would have not been found on the items, which would have assisted in the reasonable doubt case (hopefully). 

In my efforts to preempt his questions, I explained my actions in great detail, by and adding emotive language to my responses in order to seem more believable. 

I also admitted to performing other unpalatable activities (like the blackmail and the drinking on the job), to throw the scent off of my actual criminal activities; it also provided a reasonable basis for my anxious behaviour if I exhibited it at any point. 

Because of the line of work I am in, I am very aware about the strategic importance of the way information is presented. So I took some of that, the bias that comes from the fact that I am a woman and less likely to perform criminal activity, and my desire to win, to drive my case
change_strategy_free: The strategy did not change, but the way I presented my information changed to be in line with with information he had. I still ensured to be an emotional and slightly tipsy employee who was ashamed of the pettier, less criminal actions they had admitting to doing.

Deceive, Inveigle, and obfuscate. Basically I denied everything, but my answers were vague to protect me from breaking the law by lying to an investigator. I wanted to be friendly, but not helpful. I wanted to be confident, but not cocky. I wanted to be curious, but not attract further curiosity. I wanted to seem forth-coming with my answers, but I made sure to select a few questions to purposely avoid answering. For example, what did you do inside the bathroom. I wanted to make the interviewer laugh.
change_strategy_free: I did not intend to make the interviewer laugh when I was preparing. My initial plan was to stick to the story about using the bathroom. After first making the claim about my purpose inside, the investigator laughed and I decided that some light humor may help my situation. I was expecting a more serious tone from the security agent and so I had not expected humor to come into play. At the end, I felt that asking the investigator to join me for lunch was a good way to test their suspicions about me. If I was under suspicion, I expect the agent may have said yes to gain my contact information. This would help for making an arrest at a later point. When the investigator declined, I felt relieved that there was no reason to seek further contact.
